[normal]'
[normal]green
[normal]-
[normal]light
[normal]'
[normal] approach.
[normal] The Home Office commented in its 2011 paper on 
[normal]Prevent Strategy
[normal] 
[normal]as part of the 'Next Steps' agenda
[normal] that '
[normal]The Charity Commission must be seen to be capable of taking robust and vigorous action against charities that are involved in terrorist activity or have links to terrorist organisations.
[normal]' The accompanying independent survey by Lord Carlile is more candidly critical of the Commission.
[normal] 
[normal]This analysis of the 
[normal]continuing 
[normal]attitude and approach of the Charity Commission tallies with some recommendations 
[normal]in
[normal] the report by Lo
[normal]r
[normal]d Hodgson in 2012, 
[normal]Trusted and independent: giving charity back to charities - review of the Charities Act 2006
[normal].
[normal] Lord Hodgson not only calls for automatic trustee disqualification 
[normal]following any conviction of a terrorism offence
[normal] (which would not make much difference) but also that the Charity Commission should take ‘
[normal]a more robust approach to potentially failing organisations
[normal]’ and ‘
[normal]proactive as well as reactive steps
[normal]’ in cases of abuse.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]22
[normal]              
[normal]Moving next to the 
[normal]competing public 
[normal]g
[normal]oods
[normal], 
[normal]these 
[normal]countervailing considerations are that 
[normal]British 
[normal]society 
[normal]should not
[normal] appear 
[normal]to be 
[normal]stone-hearted
[normal] 
