[normal]T
[normal]he Charity Commission is wholly correct to be highly suspicious of self-serving allegations from the opponents of Palestinians, Tamils, and other oppressed peoples and to adopt a stance which is primarily encouraging of compliance with high standards of governance rather than a condemnatory approach.
[normal] 
[normal]But 
[normal]its 
[normal]serial indulgence of 
[normal]patent 
[normal]abuses does no
[normal]t 
[normal]aid
[normal] the charitable sector
[normal].  
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2
[normal]4
[normal]              
[normal]T
[normal]wo 
[normal]facile
[normal] reactions should be avoided. One 
[normal]would be
[normal] to swing entirely towards criminal prosecution and asset forfeiture, a stance which
[normal] would unduly ignore competing public goods
[normal].
[normal] The second 
[normal]mistake 
[normal]would be to 
[normal]seek to 
[normal]reinforce the 
[normal]punitive 
[normal]resolve of the Charity Commission. 
[normal]The data from this 
[normal]chapter 
[normal]suggests that 
[normal]the Commission's
[normal] 
[normal]weak 
[normal]statutory remit and 
[normal]entrenched 
[normal]‘
[normal]enabling
[normal]’ 
[normal]culture
[normal] cannot easily be nudged
[normal]. 
[normal]A
[normal] 
[normal]more 
[normal]promising
[normal] 
[normal]third way is to 
[normal]emphasise
[normal] the value of financial investigation 
[normal]to facilitate
[normal] intelligence-gathering
[normal]. P
[normal]rosecution 
[normal]and confiscation
[normal] 
[normal]remain
[normal] possible outcomes
[normal] but should be less pressing than disruption and the gathering 
[normal]and transmission 
[normal]of 
[normal]data
[normal] about terrorism activities 
[normal]other
[normal] than just financing
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2
[normal]5
[normal]              
[normal]A
[normal] financial investiga
[normal]tion approach c
[normal]ould have produced 
[normal]outcome
[normal]s
[normal] 
[normal]of greater 
[normal]utility
[normal] to counter-terrorism 
[normal]in 
[normal]several
[normal] of the inquiries described in this paper. 
[normal]I
[normal]t would have been more likely to have delivered
[normal] information 
[normal]about terrorism networks 
[normal]and 
[normal]to 
[normal]close off the facilitation of militancy, but 
[normal]without 
[normal]hurting
[normal] worthy causes.
[normal] Th
[normal]is
[normal] financial investigation approach is not best placed in the hands of the Charity Commission
[normal] but should primarily be conducted by a 
[normal]formal 
[normal]polic
[normal]e
[normal] body
[normal]. 
[normal]The roles left for the Charity Commission would be as standard-setter, 
[normal]as 
[normal]standard-monitor (with 
[normal]early 
[normal]alerts back to the police financial investigators), and 
[normal]as 
[normal]standard-applier
[normal] (with police advice)
[normal].
[normal] In this way, the heaviest price for terrorism financing 
[normal]should
[normal] be paid by 
[normal]professional profit-takers and 
[normal]recipient
[normal] perpetrators
[normal] 
[normal]of
[normal] terrorism.
